	id="Sub_TriangleInequalityInR">
	<title>Triangle Inequality for Numbers: Illustration</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>If <latex>x,y,z\in\RNr</latex>, we have the identity</para>
			<computation>
				<left>\Dstnc{x}{z}</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>\Dstnc{x}{y} + \Dstnc{y}{z}</right>
			</computation>
			<para>called the triangle inequality. This terminology is motivated by the situation in the plane depicted below:</para>
			<figure>
				<img src="ims/TriangleInequalityR2.png"></img><!-- svg available -->
			</figure>
			<para>Here we see three points <latex>P,Q,R</latex> in the plane and, in agreement with everyday experience, the distance from <latex>P</latex> to <latex>R</latex> is less than or equal to the length of the &lsquo;detour&rsquo; from <latex>P</latex> to <latex>R</latex> via <latex>Q</latex>.</para>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>